# Backup Exclusion Guidelines – Data Protection Platforms

## 1. Overview
This document defines the backup exclusion guidelines for enterprise data protection platforms. The purpose is to ensure exclusions are applied in a controlled manner without impacting system recovery, operational integrity, or security monitoring.

The guidelines apply to workloads protected by enterprise backup platforms including Cohesity, Avamar, NetWorker, and Data Domain, covering protected object types such as databases, virtual machines, file storage, and operating systems.

---

## 2. Accepted Security Policy (Conforming Use)
Backup configurations must comply with organizational security and data protection standards. Exclusions are permitted only when the excluded data does not affect:

- System or application recovery
- Security monitoring and audit capabilities
- Operational integrity of protected workloads

All exclusions must follow the defined guidelines and be documented as part of the backup governance process.

---

## 3. Exclusion Guidelines
Backup exclusions may be considered for data that does not contribute to system recovery or operational functionality.

Typical exclusion categories include:

| Data Type | Example |
|---|---|
| Temporary Files | System or application temporary directories |
| Cache Data | Application cache folders |
| Runtime Logs | High-volume runtime log files |
| Installation Artifacts | Software update or installation packages |

These exclusions are evaluated to ensure they do not remove data required for system recovery or security investigations.

Protected workloads covered by these guidelines include:

- SQL Server databases
- Oracle databases
- Virtual machines (Hyper-V, Nutanix)
- NAS and file storage (including Isilon)
- Linux servers
- Windows servers

---

## 4. Impact Guidelines

| Backup Object | Example Exclusion | Impact | Reason |
|---|---|---|---|
| Database Systems (SQL, Oracle) | Database files or transaction logs | High | Required for database integrity and recovery. |
| Virtual Machines (Hyper-V, Nutanix) | VM disk or configuration files | High | Prevents full VM recovery. |
| File Storage (NAS / Isilon / File Servers) | Business data shares | High | Contains primary business data. |
| Operating Systems (Linux / Windows) | System configuration directories | Medium | May affect rebuild or configuration restoration. |
| Application Data | Application configuration folders | Medium | May affect application functionality after restore. |
| Temporary / Runtime Data | Temp folders, cache, runtime logs | Low | Data recreated during normal operations. |

High-impact exclusions should be carefully evaluated before implementation.

---

## 5. Appendix

### Example Exclusion Locations

| Category | Example |
|---|---|
| Temporary Data | /tmp, system temporary folders |
| Cache Data | Application cache directories |
| Runtime Logs | High-volume runtime log folders |
| Update Artifacts | Downloaded software packages |

---

## 6. Definitions

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| Backup Exclusion | Configuration that prevents specific data from being included in backups |
| Persistent Data | Data required for application or system recovery |
| Runtime Data | Temporary operational data generated during execution |
| Security Telemetry | Logs or monitoring data used for detection and analysis |
| Recovery Capability | Ability to restore systems and data after an incident |

